{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8b3460b4-8181-4391-a336-e08b5e234a69","content":"Use conditional compilation directives combined with the standard `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection` registration in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.iOSNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Each platform-specific class lives under its `Platforms/<OS>` folder and implements `INotificationService`.\n- The `#if` / `#elif` preprocessor directives ensure only the relevant implementation is compiled per target, so there's no missing-type error on any platform.\n- Inject `INotificationService` via constructor injection anywhere in shared code — the correct implementation resolves automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"19157750-8939-489b-a157-ee2cad8e7dae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection — how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase-specific task.","outputTokens":354,"requestId":"1030:16EA54:15ECCBD:18946B1:69FD3631"},"id":"e08e3e47-e414-4ca2-91a4-ab3fc886385a","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:02:48.739Z","parentId":"c64d35b0-6834-4a25-bbe5-615ebae0e263"}
